    pearls: ["Proper IABP timing is critical: inflate at the dicrotic notch (onset of diastole) and deflate just before systolic upstroke. Early inflation impedes systolic ejection; late deflation increases afterload — both defeat the purpose of the device", "The most common complication is limb ischemia in the catheterized leg — perform hourly neurovascular checks (pulses, color, temperature, sensation, movement). Absent pulses require immediate vascular surgery consultation", "Never abruptly discontinue IABP — always wean gradually (1:1 → 1:2 → 1:3 → remove). Sudden cessation causes acute afterload increase that can precipitate cardiogenic shock in a compromised heart"],
